      "side": 1,
      "message": "Good questions. We are actually preventing out-of-bounds reads (so I should update the comment) - we use the index to compute a final slot index, so evaluating an expression like: u[i] turns into the slot that corresponds to \u0027u\u0027, adjusted by \u0027i\u0027 * stride. Then we have an skvm::Val stored in fSlots, so we\u0027d end up possibly fetching outside the bounds of fSlots in that case.\n\nAs for the control flow - unlike the index, we can\u0027t guarantee that it\u0027s immediate here:\n\n  uniform half4 color_stops[3];\n  half4 main(float2 p) {\n    return p.x \u003c 0 ? color_stops[0]\n         : p.x \u003c 1 ? color_stops[1]\n         :           color_stops[2];\n  }\n\nUnfortunately, I think you\u0027re on to something - the combination of the two different systems means we should statically reject compilation of something like:\n\n  int arr[1];\n  for (int i \u003d 7; i \u003c 10; ++i) { arr[i]++; }\n\n... but we won\u0027t. The front-end only validates the bounds of index-by-literal. Going to hold off on landing this until I think about it some more.",
